[TextBlock(text='[
  {
    "sid": "50094",
    "Technique ID": "T1553",
    "Technique name": "Subvert Trust Controls",
    "Quotes": ["'Adversaries may undermine security controls that will either warn users of untrusted activity or prevent execution of untrusted programs'"],
    "Explanation": "The Snort rule detects an HTTP attack attempt that involves poisoning the Responder service, which is a technique used to subvert trust controls and bypass security mechanisms. The rule looks for a specific pattern in the HTTP request that indicates an attempt to load a malicious image from an untrusted source (file://RespProxySrv/pictures/logo.jpg), which could potentially be used to execute untrusted code or bypass security controls."
  }
]', type='text')][TextBlock(text='[
  {
    "sid": "50094",
    "Technique ID": "T1556",
    "Technique name": "Modify Authentication Process",
    "Quotes": ["Adversaries may modify authentication mechanisms and processes to access user credentials or enable otherwise unwarranted access to accounts"],
    "Explanation": "The Snort rule detects an HTTP attack attempt related to the Responder poisoner, which is a tool used to perform LLMNR/NBT-NS poisoning attacks. This technique involves modifying the authentication process by responding to LLMNR/NBT-NS requests with spoofed responses, allowing an attacker to capture credentials and gain unauthorized access to accounts."
  }
]', type='text')][TextBlock(text='[
  {
    "sid": "50094",
    "Technique ID": "T1185",
    "Technique name": "Browser Session Hijacking",
    "Quotes": ["'Adversaries may take advantage of security vulnerabilities and inherent functionality in browser software to change content, modify user-behaviors, and intercept information as part of various browser session hijacking techniques'"],
    "Explanation": "The Snort rule detects an HTTP attack attempt that involves injecting malicious content (an image tag with a file URI) into the client's browser session, which could potentially lead to session hijacking or other browser-based attacks."
  }
]', type='text')][TextBlock(text='[
  {
    "sid": "50094",
    "Technique ID": "T1498",
    "Technique name": "Network Denial of Service",
    "Quotes": ["The rule detects an HTTP attack attempt that could potentially lead to a network denial of service condition."],
    "Explanation": "The rule is designed to detect a specific type of HTTP attack known as a 'Responder poisoner' attack, which is a technique used to perform network denial of service attacks by exploiting vulnerabilities in the Responder service on Windows systems. This attack can potentially overwhelm network resources and disrupt legitimate network traffic, aligning with the 'Network Denial of Service' technique from MITRE ATT&CK."
  }
]', type='text')][TextBlock(text='[
  {
    "sid": "50094",
    "Technique ID": "T1566",
    "Technique name": "Phishing",
    "Quotes": ["'Adversaries may send phishing messages to gain access to victim systems'"],
    "Explanation": "The Snort rule detects an HTTP attack attempt related to a Responder poisoner, which is a type of phishing attack that aims to redirect users to a malicious website by spoofing legitimate network resources. This technique is used by adversaries to gain initial access to victim systems."
  }
]', type='text')][TextBlock(text='[
  {
    "sid": "50094",
    "Technique ID": "T1190",
    "Technique name": "Exploit Public-Facing Application",
    "Quotes": ["'Adversaries may attempt to exploit a weakness in an Internet-facing host or system to initially access a network'"],
    "Explanation": "The Snort rule detects an HTTP attack attempt that exploits a vulnerability in the Responder service, which is a public-facing application. This aligns with the technique 'Exploit Public-Facing Application' where adversaries exploit weaknesses in Internet-facing systems to gain initial access to a network."
  }
]', type='text')][TextBlock(text='[
  {
    "sid": "50094",
    "Technique ID": "T1036",
    "Technique name": "Masquerading",
    "Quotes": ["'Adversaries may attempt to manipulate features of their artifacts to make them appear legitimate or benign to users and/or security tools'"],
    "Explanation": "The Snort rule detects an HTTP attack attempt where the attacker tries to masquerade as a legitimate file request by using the 'file://' protocol handler to retrieve a malicious image file from a remote server. This falls under the 'Masquerading' technique, where adversaries manipulate their artifacts to appear benign."
  }
]', type='text')][TextBlock(text='[
  {
    "sid": "50094",
    "Technique ID": "T1221",
    "Technique name": "Template Injection",
    "Quotes": ["'Adversaries may create or modify references in user document templates to conceal malicious code or force authentication attempts'"],
    "Explanation": "The Snort rule detects an HTTP attack attempt that involves injecting a malicious image source URL into a web page, which could be an attempt to exploit a template injection vulnerability. Template injection attacks allow adversaries to inject malicious code or references into web application templates, potentially leading to remote code execution or other malicious actions."
  }
]', type='text')][TextBlock(text='[
  {
    "sid": "50094",
    "Technique ID": "T1557",
    "Technique name": "Adversary-in-the-Middle",
    "Quotes": ["Adversaries may attempt to position themselves between two or more networked devices using an adversary-in-the-middle (AiTM) technique to support follow-on behaviors such as Network Sniffing, Transmitted Data Manipulation, or replay attacks (Exploitation for Credential Access)"],
    "Explanation": "The Snort rule detects an HTTP attack attempt related to the Responder poisoner, which is a tool used for performing an Adversary-in-the-Middle (AiTM) attack by poisoning the browser cache and redirecting traffic through a malicious proxy server. This technique allows the adversary to intercept and manipulate network traffic between the victim and other systems."
  }
]', type='text')][TextBlock(text='[
    {
        "sid": "50094",
        "Technique ID": "T1565",
        "Technique name": "Data Manipulation",
        "Quotes": ["'Adversaries may insert, delete, or manipulate data in order to influence external outcomes or hide activity, thus threatening the integrity of the data'"],
        "Explanation": "The Snort rule detects an HTTP attack attempt that involves manipulating the image source URL to load a malicious file from a remote location (file://RespProxySrv/pictures/logo.jpg). This manipulation of the image source data is an attempt to compromise the integrity of the web content, aligning with the Data Manipulation technique."
    }
]', type='text')][TextBlock(text='[
    {
        "sid": "50094",
        "Technique ID": "T1189",
        "Technique name": "Drive-by Compromise",
        "Quotes": ["\"Adversaries may gain access to a system through a user visiting a website over the normal course of browsing\""],
        "Explanation": "The Snort rule detects an HTTP attack attempt that involves embedding a malicious image source URL in an attempt to exploit the Responder service on the client system. This aligns with the Drive-by Compromise technique, where adversaries gain access to a system by luring users to visit a compromised website."
    }
]', type='text')]

[TextBlock(text='[
    {
        "sid": "38563",
        "Technique ID": "T1056",
        "Technique name": "Input Capture",
        "Quotes": ["\"Input Capture techniques involve intercepting and capturing user input data, such as keystrokes, to obtain sensitive information.\""],
        "Explanation": "The rule indicates the presence of a Trojan (GateKeylogger) that mimics a '404 Not Found' error to disguise its communication with a command and control server, which is a common method used by keyloggers to stealthily capture input data."
    },
    {
        "sid": "38563", 
        "Technique ID": "T1608",
        "Technique name": "Stage Capabilities",
        "Quotes": ["\"Adversaries may upload, install, or otherwise set up capabilities that can be used during targeting\""],
        "Explanation": "The rule detects a Trojan (GateKeylogger) that is likely staged on the compromised system to capture user input and communicate with a command and control server."
    }
]', type='text')][TextBlock(text='[
    {
        "sid": "38563",
        "Technique ID": "T1056",
        "Technique name": "Input Capture",
        "Quotes": ["\"Input Capture techniques involve intercepting and capturing user input data, such as keystrokes, to obtain sensitive information.\""],
        "Explanation": "The Snort rule detects activity related to the Win.Trojan.GateKeylogger malware, which is a keylogger that captures user input data. The rule looks for a fake '404 Not Found' response from the malware, which is a common technique used by keyloggers to disguise their communication with a command and control server while capturing keystrokes."
    },
    {
        "sid": "38563",
        "Technique ID": "T1104",
        "Technique name": "Multi-Stage Channels",
        "Quotes": ["\"Adversaries may create multiple stages for command and control that are employed under different conditions or for certain functions\""],
        "Explanation": "The Snort rule suggests that the Win.Trojan.GateKeylogger malware uses a multi-stage command and control channel, where it first communicates with a server using a fake '404 Not Found' response, potentially to evade detection or bypass security controls, before establishing a more direct communication channel for exfiltrating captured data."
    }
]', type='text')][TextBlock(text='[
  {
    "sid": "38563",
    "Technique ID": "T1056",
    "Technique name": "Input Capture",
    "Quotes": ["\"Adversaries may collect data stored in the clipboard from users copying information within or between applications\""],
    "Explanation": "The Snort rule detects activity related to the Win.Trojan.GateKeylogger malware, which is designed to capture user input data, such as keystrokes. This aligns with the Input Capture technique (T1056) described in the MITRE ATT&CK framework."
  },
  {
    "sid": "38563", 
    "Technique ID": "T1185",
    "Technique name": "Browser Session Hijacking",
    "Quotes": ["\"Adversaries may take advantage of security vulnerabilities and inherent functionality in browser software to change content, modify user-behaviors, and intercept information as part of various browser session hijacking techniques\""],
    "Explanation": "The Snort rule mentions that the malware sends a fake '404 Not Found' response, which could be an attempt to hijack the browser session and intercept information, aligning with the Browser Session Hijacking technique (T1185)."
  }
]', type='text')][TextBlock(text='[
    {
        "sid": "38563",
        "Technique ID": "T1056",
        "Technique name": "Input Capture",
        "Quotes": ["\"Input Capture techniques involve intercepting and capturing user input data, such as keystrokes, to obtain sensitive information.\""],
        "Explanation": "The rule indicates the presence of a Trojan (GateKeylogger) that mimics a '404 Not Found' error to disguise its communication with a command and control server, which is a common method used by keyloggers to stealthily capture input data."
    },
    {
        "sid": "38563",
        "Technique ID": "T1071",
        "Technique name": "Application Layer Protocol",
        "Quotes": ["\"Adversaries may use an application layer protocol for communication between host and C2 server or among hosts within a network.\""],
        "Explanation": "The rule detects communication between the Trojan and a command and control server using the HTTP protocol, which is an application layer protocol."
    }
]', type='text')][TextBlock(text='[
    {
        "sid": "38563",
        "Technique ID": "T1056",
        "Technique name": "Input Capture",
        "Quotes": ["\"Input Capture techniques involve intercepting and capturing user input data, such as keystrokes, to obtain sensitive information.\""],
        "Explanation": "The Snort rule detects activity related to the Win.Trojan.GateKeylogger malware, which is a keylogger trojan that captures user input data like keystrokes. This aligns with the Input Capture technique (T1056) from MITRE ATT&CK."
    },
    {
        "sid": "38563", 
        "Technique ID": "T1090",
        "Technique name": "Proxy",
        "Quotes": ["\"Adversaries may use a connection proxy to direct network traffic between systems or act as an intermediary for network communications to a command and control server to avoid direct connections to their infrastructure.\""],
        "Explanation": "The Snort rule mentions 'MALWARE-CNC', which suggests the presence of a command and control (C2) server. Malware like keyloggers often use proxies or intermediary servers to communicate with their C2 infrastructure, avoiding direct connections. This relates to the Proxy technique (T1090) from MITRE ATT&CK."
    }
]', type='text')][TextBlock(text='[
    {
        "sid": "38563",
        "Technique ID": "T1056",
        "Technique name": "Input Capture",
        "Quotes": ["\"Adversaries may gather credential material by invoking or forcing a user to automatically provide authentication information through a mechanism in which they can intercept\""],
        "Explanation": "The Snort rule detects activity related to the Win.Trojan.GateKeylogger malware, which is designed to capture user input data such as keystrokes. This aligns with the Input Capture technique (T1056) described in the MITRE ATT&CK framework."
    },
    {
        "sid": "38563", 
        "Technique ID": "T1008",
        "Technique name": "Fallback Channels",
        "Quotes": ["\"Adversaries may use fallback or alternate communication channels if the primary channel is compromised or inaccessible in order to maintain reliable command and control and to avoid data transfer thresholds\""],
        "Explanation": "The rule mentions 'MALWARE-CNC', indicating the detection of a command and control (C2) channel used by malware. Malware often employs fallback channels (T1008) as a backup mechanism for maintaining C2 communications if the primary channel is disrupted or detected."
    }
]', type='text')][TextBlock(text='[
    {
        "sid": "38563",
        "Technique ID": "T1036",
        "Technique name": "Masquerading",
        "Quotes": ["\"Adversaries may attempt to manipulate features of their artifacts to make them appear legitimate or benign to users and/or security tools\""],
        "Explanation": "The Snort rule detects a Trojan (GateKeylogger) that masquerades as a '404 Not Found' error to disguise its communication with a command and control server, which aligns with the Masquerading technique where adversaries manipulate their artifacts to appear benign."
    },
    {
        "sid": "38563",
        "Technique ID": "T1056",
        "Technique name": "Input Capture",
        "Quotes": ["\"Adversaries may use methods of capturing user input to obtain credentials or collect information\""],
        "Explanation": "The rule specifically mentions 'Win.Trojan.GateKeylogger', which is a keylogger Trojan that captures user input data, such as keystrokes, to obtain sensitive information like credentials. This directly relates to the Input Capture technique."
    }
]', type='text')][TextBlock(text='[
        "sid": "38563",
        "Technique ID": "T1102",
        "Technique name": "Web Service",
        "Quotes": ["Adversaries may use an existing, legitimate external Web service as a means for relaying data to/from a compromised system"],
        "Explanation": "The Snort rule detects a Trojan (GateKeylogger) that communicates with a command and control server by mimicking a '404 Not Found' error response, which aligns with the use of a web service for malicious communication as described in the T1102 technique."
    ]', type='text')][TextBlock(text='[
    {
        "sid": "38563",
        "Technique ID": "T1056",
        "Technique name": "Input Capture",
        "Quotes": ["\"Input Capture techniques involve intercepting and capturing user input data, such as keystrokes, to obtain sensitive information.\""],
        "Explanation": "The Snort rule detects activity related to the Win.Trojan.GateKeylogger malware, which is a keylogger trojan that captures user input data. The rule looks for a fake '404 Not Found' response from the malware, which is a common technique used by keyloggers to disguise their communication with a command and control server while capturing keystrokes."
    },
    {
        "sid": "38563",
        "Technique ID": "T1071",
        "Technique name": "Application Layer Protocol",
        "Quotes": ["\"Adversaries may communicate using OSI application layer protocols to avoid detection/network filtering by blending in with existing traffic\""],
        "Explanation": "The Snort rule is specifically looking for HTTP traffic, which is an application layer protocol. The malware is using HTTP to communicate with its command and control server, likely to blend in with legitimate web traffic and avoid detection."
    }
]', type='text')][TextBlock(text='[
    {
        "sid": "38563",
        "Technique ID": "T1132",
        "Technique name": "Data Encoding",
        "Quotes": ["\"Adversaries may encode data to make the content of command and control traffic more difficult to detect\""],
        "Explanation": "The rule detects a malware (Win.Trojan.GateKeylogger) that uses a fake '404 Not Found' error message to disguise its command and control communication, which suggests the use of data encoding techniques to obfuscate the malicious traffic."
    },
    {
        "sid": "38563",
        "Technique ID": "T1001",
        "Technique name": "Data Obfuscation",
        "Quotes": ["\"Adversaries may obfuscate command and control traffic to make it more difficult to detect\""],
        "Explanation": "The rule detects a malware (Win.Trojan.GateKeylogger) that uses a fake '404 Not Found' error message to obfuscate its command and control communication, which is a form of data obfuscation to evade detection."
    }
]', type='text')][TextBlock(text='[
        "sid": "38563",
        "Technique ID": "T1041",
        "Technique name": "Exfiltration Over C2 Channel",
        "Quotes": ["\"Adversaries may steal data by exfiltrating it over an existing command and control channel\""],
        "Explanation": "The Snort rule detects a Trojan (GateKeylogger) that communicates with a command and control server, potentially exfiltrating captured data over the same channel. This aligns with the technique of Exfiltration Over C2 Channel, where adversaries steal data by sending it through an existing command and control communication channel."
    ]', type='text')]

[TextBlock(text='[
  {
    "sid": "976",
    "Technique ID": "T1518",
    "Technique name": "Software Discovery",
    "Quotes": ["'Adversaries may attempt to get a listing of software and software versions that are installed on a system or in a cloud environment'"],
    "Explanation": "The Snort rule is designed to detect attempts to access .bat files, which are batch script files used in Windows systems. This could be an indication of an adversary trying to discover and potentially exploit software installed on the target system, aligning with the Software Discovery technique."
  }
]', type='text')][TextBlock(text='[
  {
    "sid": "976",
    "Technique ID": "T1046",
    "Technique name": "Network Service Discovery",
    "Quotes": ["'Adversaries may attempt to get a listing of services running on remote hosts and local network infrastructure devices, including those that may be vulnerable to remote software exploitation'"],
    "Explanation": "The Snort rule is designed to detect attempts to access .bat files on web servers, which could be an indication of an adversary trying to discover and exploit vulnerable services running on the server."
  }
]', type='text')][TextBlock(text='[
  {
    "sid": "976",
    "Technique ID": "T1059",
    "Technique name": "Command and Scripting Interpreter",
    "Quotes": ["\"Adversaries may abuse command and script interpreters to execute commands, scripts, or binaries\""],
    "Explanation": "The Snort rule is designed to detect attempts to access .bat files, which are batch script files used in Windows systems to execute commands and scripts. This aligns with the Command and Scripting Interpreter technique, where adversaries abuse interpreters like cmd.exe to execute malicious commands or scripts."
  }
]', type='text')][TextBlock(text='[
  {
    "sid": "976",
    "Technique ID": "T1505",
    "Technique name": "Server Software Component",
    "Quotes": ["\"Adversaries may abuse legitimate extensible development features of servers to establish persistent access to systems\""],
    "Explanation": "The Snort rule is designed to detect attempts to access .bat files through the /cgi-bin/ directory on web servers, which could indicate an attempt to abuse server software components for malicious purposes, such as executing arbitrary code or establishing persistent access."
  }
]', type='text')][TextBlock(text='[
  {
    "sid": "976",
    "Technique ID": "T1505",
    "Technique name": "Server Software Component",
    "Quotes": ["Adversaries may attempt to execute malicious content by taking advantage of web server software components to bypass application and platform control measures."],
    "Explanation": "The Snort rule detects attempts to access .bat files via the /cgi-bin/ directory on web servers, which could indicate an attempt to execute malicious code by exploiting vulnerabilities in web server software components."
  }
]', type='text')][TextBlock(text='[
  {
    "sid": "976",
    "Technique ID": "T1190",
    "Technique name": "Exploit Public-Facing Application",
    "Quotes": ["'Adversaries may attempt to exploit a weakness in an Internet-facing host or system to initially access a network'"],
    "Explanation": "The Snort rule is designed to detect potential exploitation attempts against web servers by monitoring for requests containing '.bat?' in the URI, which could indicate an attempt to access or execute batch scripts on the server. This aligns with the technique of exploiting public-facing applications to gain initial access to a network."
  },
  {
    "sid": "976",
    "Technique ID": "T1211",
    "Technique name": "Exploitation for Defense Evasion",
    "Quotes": ["'Adversaries may exploit a system or application vulnerability to bypass security features'"],
    "Explanation": "The rule is specifically looking for requests that could potentially exploit vulnerabilities in web applications to bypass security controls and execute unauthorized code or scripts on the server. This relates to the technique of exploiting vulnerabilities for defense evasion purposes."
  }
]', type='text')][TextBlock(text='[
  {
    "sid": "976",
    "Technique ID": "T1202",
    "Technique name": "Indirect Command Execution",
    "Quotes": ["'Adversaries may abuse utilities that allow for command execution to bypass security restrictions that limit the use of command-line interpreters'"],
    "Explanation": "The Snort rule is designed to detect attempts to access .bat files, which are batch script files used for executing commands on Windows systems. This could be an indication of an adversary attempting to execute commands indirectly by abusing the batch script interpreter, potentially bypassing security restrictions on direct command execution."
  }
]', type='text')][TextBlock(text='[
  {
    "sid": "976",
    "Technique ID": "T1047",
    "Technique name": "Windows Management Instrumentation",
    "Quotes": ["'Adversaries may abuse Windows Management Instrumentation (WMI) to execute malicious commands and payloads'"],
    "Explanation": "The Snort rule is designed to detect attempts to access .bat files, which are Windows batch script files often used for executing commands on Windows systems. While the rule does not explicitly mention WMI, the ability to execute batch scripts could potentially be leveraged by an adversary to abuse WMI for executing malicious payloads or commands."
  },
  {
    "sid": "976",
    "Technique ID": "T1204",
    "Technique name": "User Execution",
    "Quotes": ["'An adversary may rely upon specific actions by a user in order to gain execution'"],
    "Explanation": "The Snort rule is looking for attempts to access .bat files, which could be an indication of an adversary trying to trick a user into executing a malicious batch script, thereby relying on user execution to gain a foothold on the system."
  }
]', type='text')][TextBlock(text='[
  {
    "sid": "976",
    "Technique ID": "T1071",
    "Technique name": "Application Layer Protocol",
    "Quotes": ["Adversaries may communicate using OSI application layer protocols to avoid detection/network filtering by blending in with existing traffic"],
    "Explanation": "The Snort rule is designed to detect HTTP requests for '.bat?' files, which could be an attempt by an adversary to blend in with legitimate web traffic while delivering malicious payloads or executing commands on the server. This aligns with the 'Application Layer Protocol' technique, where adversaries use application layer protocols like HTTP to avoid detection."
  }
]', type='text')][TextBlock(text='[
  {
    "sid": "976",
    "Technique ID": "T1505",
    "Technique name": "Server Software Component",
    "Quotes": ["Adversaries may attempt to take advantage of trusted server software components to execute code or bypass authentication."],
    "Explanation": "The Snort rule is designed to detect attempts to access .bat files through the /cgi-bin/ directory on web servers, which could indicate an attempt to exploit vulnerabilities in server software components like CGI scripts to execute arbitrary code or gain unauthorized access."
  }
]', type='text')][TextBlock(text='[
    {
        "sid": "976",
        "Technique ID": "T1190",
        "Technique name": "Exploit Public-Facing Application",
        "Quotes": ["Adversaries may attempt to take advantage of a weakness in an Internet-facing computer or program using software, data, or commands in order to cause unintended or unanticipated behavior."],
        "Explanation": "The Snort rule is designed to detect attempts to access .bat files through a web server's cgi-bin directory, which could indicate an attempt to exploit a public-facing web application. This aligns with the T1190 technique, where adversaries try to exploit vulnerabilities in Internet-facing applications to gain unauthorized access or cause unintended behavior."
    }
]', type='text')]

[TextBlock(text='[
  {
    "sid": "1129",
    "Technique ID": "T1170",
    "Technique name": "Browser Extensions",
    "Quotes": ["Adversaries may abuse browser extensions to bypass web browser security policies or establish a persistent point of access in one of the most common user platforms."],
    "Explanation": "The Snort rule is designed to detect attempts to access the .htaccess file, which is a configuration file used by Apache web servers to control access and permissions. While not directly related to browser extensions, this rule could potentially detect attempts by malicious browser extensions to access sensitive web server configuration files for reconnaissance or exploitation purposes."
  }
]', type='text')][TextBlock(text='[
  {
    "sid": "1129",
    "Technique ID": "T1046",
    "Technique name": "Network Service Discovery",
    "Quotes": ["Adversaries may attempt to get a listing of services running on remote hosts and local network infrastructure devices, including those that may be vulnerable to remote software exploitation"],
    "Explanation": "The Snort rule is designed to detect attempts to access the .htaccess file on web servers, which is often used for reconnaissance purposes to gather information about the server's configuration and potentially identify vulnerabilities. This aligns with the Network Service Discovery technique, where adversaries try to enumerate services running on remote systems as a precursor to exploitation."
  }
]', type='text')][TextBlock(text='[
  {
    "sid": "1129",
    "Technique ID": "T1170",
    "Technique name": "Browser Extensions",
    "Quotes": ["Adversaries may abuse browser extensions to bypass web browser security policies or establish a persistent point of access in one of the most common user applications."],
    "Explanation": "The Snort rule is designed to detect attempts to access the .htaccess file, which is a configuration file used by Apache web servers to control access and functionality. While the T1170 technique is primarily focused on browser extensions, the rule's detection of .htaccess access could be related to reconnaissance activities or attempts to gain unauthorized access to web server configurations, which aligns with the broader goals of the T1170 technique."
  }
]', type='text')][TextBlock(text='[
  {
    "sid": "1129",
    "Technique ID": "T1170",
    "Technique name": "Browser Extensions",
    "Quotes": ["Adversaries may abuse browser extensions to establish persistent access to systems."],
    "Explanation": "While the Snort rule does not directly mention browser extensions, it detects attempts to access the .htaccess file, which is a configuration file used by Apache web servers to control access and functionality. Malicious actors could potentially abuse .htaccess files to enable browser extensions or other malicious code on the web server, aligning with the T1170 technique."
  }
]', type='text')][TextBlock(text='[
    {
        "sid": "1129",
        "Technique ID": "T1170",
        "Technique name": "Automated Collection",
        "Quotes": ["Adversaries may attempt to gather information about attached peripheral devices and components connected to a computer system"],
        "Explanation": "The Snort rule detects attempts to access the .htaccess file, which is a configuration file used by Apache web servers to control access and behavior for specific directories. Accessing this file could be an attempt to gather information about the web server configuration, which aligns with the 'Automated Collection' technique of gathering system information."
    }
]', type='text')][TextBlock(text='[
  {
    "sid": "1129",
    "Technique ID": "T1083",
    "Technique name": "File and Directory Discovery",
    "Quotes": ["Adversaries may enumerate files and directories or may search in specific locations of a host or network share for certain information within a file system"],
    "Explanation": "The Snort rule is designed to detect attempts to access the .htaccess file, which is a configuration file used by Apache web servers to control access permissions and other settings. This activity falls under the 'File and Directory Discovery' technique, where an adversary tries to enumerate files and directories on the target system to gather information or find sensitive data."
  }
]', type='text')][TextBlock(text='[
  {
    "sid": "1129",
    "Technique ID": "T1036",
    "Technique name": "Masquerading",
    "Quotes": ["Adversaries may attempt to manipulate features of their artifacts to make them appear legitimate or benign to users and/or security tools"],
    "Explanation": "The Snort rule is designed to detect attempts to access the .htaccess file, which is a configuration file used by Apache web servers to control access and behavior. Adversaries may try to access or modify this file to masquerade their activities as legitimate web server operations, evading detection or gaining unauthorized access."
  }
